###Feedback This set of graphs is a really good starting point for your portfolio and I thought you were strategic in the order that you set your plots up in giving the overall frequency picture in the first graph, then moving into the specifics with the subsequent ones. I used the argument ggarrange() to package the Activity and Sedentary plots together, but you might even think about displaying all four graphs together as one visualization. The use of the age cutoffs by color really helps the distribution to be visualized in chucks, so great call on that. One area that could help the Physical Activity plots is to clean up the x-axis ticks by using theme(). One other suggested change that I played with was adding theme_minimal().

  geom_encircle(aes(mod_work, vig_work),

###Feedback You do a great job of packaging the plots together in order to tell a comprehensive story. You may want to try ggarrage() here also, but I will leave that call to you. I went ahead and used theme_minimal() again and also tried ColorBrewers Dark2 theme on the second plot. One of the issues that I am having on my own plots with viridis is that it plots qualitative data in a gradient so that it does not actually look qualitative. I am sure Daniel has an easy fix, but one way is to go with another palette maker.
